# Testing — principles (agnostic)

## Desired state

Automated tests **document behavior** and **guard refactors**. The suite is **shaped** so fast feedback and confidence coexist: many small, isolated checks; fewer integration checks; a thin layer of end-to-end checks as appropriate to the product.

## Properties

- **P1 (TDD loop)**: Preferred workflow: express intent as a failing test → make it pass with minimal code → refactor while keeping tests green. (Teams may time-box or apply selectively for exploration-only code, but the default policy favors test-first for production logic.)
- **P2 (pyramid)**: The majority of tests are **fast and isolated**; **integration** tests assert adapters and composition; **E2E** tests cover critical paths. Inverted pyramids (mostly slow UI-only tests) are avoided for new work.
- **P3 (AAA)**: Each test is structured in **Arrange** (context), **Act** (single behavior), **Assert** (expected outcomes). Multiple unrelated assertions in one “story” are discouraged unless they describe the same behavior outcome.
- **P4 (naming)**: Test names or descriptions state **expected behavior** and **relevant condition** (for example: “rejects when total is negative”).
- **P5 (boundaries)**: **Doubles, fakes, or stubs** are used at **ports**; internal implementation details are not overly mocked.

## Anti-patterns

- Large integration tests with no fast unit tests for pure logic.
- Tests that only mirror implementation (e.g. assert private helpers) instead of behavior.
- Writing production code for non-trivial behavior without a failing test when TDD is the team policy.

## Examples (Go — table-driven)

```go
func TestPriceWithTax(t *testing.T) {
    tests := []struct {
        name string
        in   int64
        rate float64
        want int64
    }{
        {"round trip", 1000, 0.2, 1200},
    }
    for _, tc := range tests {
        t.Run(tc.name, func(t *testing.T) {
            got, err := domain.PriceWithTax(tc.in, tc.rate)
            if err != nil {
                t.Fatal(err)
            }
            if got != tc.want {
                t.Errorf("got %d want %d", got, tc.want)
            }
        })
    }
}
```

